      {{#> column-layout--default}}
        <h3 class="article_headline">Step 2. Quantity</h3>
        <p>Select the number of units you want to buy or sell.</p>
      {{/column-layout--default}}

      {{#> column-layout--default}}
        <h4 class="article_subhead">Understanding Quantities</h4>
        <p>To purchase one unit or futures contract does not mean you are purchasing a single cob or even stalk of corn. In fact, one futures contract of corn is equal to 5,000 bushels.</p>
      {{/column-layout--default}}

      {{#> column-layout--default}}
        <h3 class="article_headline">Step 3. Buying vs. Selling</h3>
        <p>Unlike stocks, you can sell futures without making a previous purchase. However, you cannot realize a profit in futures trading until you “flatten” your position – placing an order for the same quantity on the opposite side of the market.</p>
        <p>If that rainfall has you thinking that prices in the corn market will spike, you'll purchase one corn futures contract in anticipation of that potential rise.</p>
        <p>On the other hand, if that bumper crop came through and supply is set to exceed demand, you’ll sell in anticipation of a downward trend in prices.</p>
      {{/column-layout--default}}

